A '''Finnish heritage disease''' is a genetic disease or disorder that is significantly more common in people whose ancestors were ethnic [[Finns]], natives of [[Finland]] and [[Sweden]].  About 40 [[rare disease]]s are regarded as Finnish heritage diseases.<ref name="pmid12627297">{{cite journal
| author = Norio R
| title = The Finnish Disease Heritage III: the individual diseases
| journal = Human Genetics
| volume = 112
| issue = 5-6
| pages = 470–526
| year = 2003
| month = May
| pmid = 12627297
| doi = 10.1007/s00439-002-0877-1
| url = 
| issn = 
}}</ref>  The diseases are not restricted to Finns;  they are genetic diseases with far wider distribution in the world, but due to [[founder effect]]s and [[Genetic isolate|genetic isolation]] they are more common in Finns.

Within [[Finland]] these diseases are more common in the east and north, consistent with their higher association with ethnic Finns than with ethnic [[Swedish people|Swedes]].<ref name="pmid19367325">{{cite journal
| author = Palo JU, Ulmanen I, Lukka M, Ellonen P, Sajantila A
| title = Genetic markers and population history: Finland revisited
| journal = European Journal of Human Genetics
| volume = 17
| issue = 10
| pages = 1336–46
| year = 2009
| month = April
| pmid = 19367325
| pmc = 2986642
| doi = 10.1038/ejhg.2009.53
| url = 
| issn = 
}}</ref>  The Finnish disease heritage does not extend to other ethnic groups in the region, the [[Sami people|Sámi]] and [[Karelians]] other than [[Karelia (historical province of Finland)|Finnish Karelians]].  It is attributed to a [[population bottleneck]] among ancestors of modern Finns, estimated to have occurred about 4000 years ago, presumably when populations practicing agriculture and animal husbandry arrived in Finland.<ref name="pmid8876258"/>

In Finland about one in five persons carries a gene defect associated with at least one Finnish heritage disease, and about one in 500 children born is affected.<ref name="pmid11360285">{{cite journal
| author = Kallinen J, Heinonen S, Palotie A, Mannermaa A, Ryynanen M
| title = Antenatal gene tests in low-risk pregnancies: molecular screening for aspartylglucosaminuria (AGU) and infantile neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis (INCL) in Finland
| journal = Prenatal Diagnosis
| volume = 21
| issue = 5
| pages = 409–12
| year = 2001
| month = May
| pmid = 11360285
| doi = 10.1002/pd.82
| url = 
| issn = 
}}</ref>  Most of the gene defects are [[autosomal]] [[recessive]]s, so that if both the mother and father carry the same defect, the chance that their child will have the associated disease is 1 in 4.  The [[molecular genetics]] of many of these diseases have been determined, enabling [[genetic testing]], [[prenatal testing]], and counseling.  This has raised questions of [[bioethics]] and [[eugenics]].<ref>{{cite book
|chapter=3:  The first genetic screening in Finland: its execution, evaluation, and some possible implications for liberal government
|author=Seppo Poutanen
|title=Genetic governance:  Health, risk, and ethics in the biotech era
|editor=Robin Bunton and Alan Petersen
|year=2005
|publisher=Routledge
|isbn=0-415-35407-2
|pages=215
|url=http://books.google.com/?id=cKxl1JOVQLQC
}}</ref>

